            "replies_count": 0,
            "reblogs_count": 0,
            "favourites_count": 0,
            "edited_at": null,
            "content": "<p><span class=\"h-card\" translate=\"no\"><a href=\"https://tldr.nettime.org/@remixtures\" class=\"u-url mention\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">@<span>remixtures</span></a></span></p><p>\"How do we live well on this planet without destroying it?\"</p><p>\"Infinite growth on a finite planet is not feasible.\"</p><p>The GDP calculation is flawed.  As indicated in the video, GDP only accounts for the market value of everything we produce - but it does not take into account the social and ecological costs of production.</p><p>As a result, damage to the environment and then repairing it makes it look like it's good for the economy and good for progress - but *IT'S NOT*.</p><p>Production comes in two forms - beneficial and destructive.</p><p>What can we do to become a sustainable society?</p><p><a href=\"https://c.im/tags/gdp\" class=\"mention hashtag\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">#<span>gdp</span></a> <a href=\"https://c.im/tags/degrowth\" class=\"mention hashtag\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">#<span>degrowth</span></a> <a href=\"https://c.im/tags/overshoot\" class=\"mention hashtag\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">#<span>overshoot</span></a></p>",
